##Oral record | more than a month, I sleep with heart-saving pills in the first line of epidemic prevention

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

February 20th is my 50th birthday. One day I was at my checkpoint when my wife called me up and said she had ordered a song for me on the radio to wish me a happy birthday. When I heard it, I was familiar with Aaron Kwok's endless love for you when I was young.

Oral | Hu Junhua

Arrangement | Wang Yu

I don't know how long I slept, but I woke up. Looking out of the window, I could tell it was still night because the lights at the crossing and the traffic lights were still on. The clock said it was the middle of the night, so I got up and went to the checkpoint to check on my colleagues.

This is the G60 Shanghai-kunming Expressway, Fengjing police checkpoint. Daokou is originally all around the wind, the early morning cold wind is biting, if only wear a coat is not enough to keep out the cold. I'm used to this kind of environment, and many of them are volunteers in various fields to support the fight against the epidemic, and have not experienced similar situations, many of them are young people.

A car came, our staff to meet up, ask for information, do registration, temperature, and as seriously as usual in place. I checked to see if they were dressed enough and went to a temporary rest stop to make sure that everyone who had just finished their shift had a warm ginger soup to drink and a hand warmer. I'm relieved to see that all of this is normal.

I've been sleeping at the checkpoint every day for over a month. I can't remember which day I can sleep for a few hours, only I know that the whole biological clock is in disorder, no matter how late at night, whenever there is something at the crossing, I get up to deal with it; even if I close my eyes, i kept wondering if there were any new problems, and sometimes I had to take pills to get some sleep.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
During the anti-epidemic period, Hu Junhua was in the command room of the checkpoint

The most tired or the end of January, epidemic prevention work just began that period of time.

On the evening of January 26, I received a notice that the epidemic prevention and control measures in Shanghai would be upgraded. The work of prevention, control and inspection at the checkpoint would be fully started at 2 p.m. on January 27, and it was made clear that the "station master is responsible for the system. ". That means I am the first responsible person at this juncture.

In the past, when I worked here, I only had to take charge of public security. But this time, in addition to public security leading, I also had to coordinate various departments, such as health, transportation, urban management and volunteers, to work out a full set of work programs. Gave me less than 20 hours.

In fact, time is not the most difficult, the most difficult thing is that I had never worked out such a plan at all: before, whether it was a routine inspection or a guarantee for major activities, whether it was checking people, vehicles or objects, it was all visible, but this time we want to check the invisible virus, and every car everyone must check, can not miss any one.

No matter how hard it is, you have to go on top. Because I am the general commander of this site, the program does not come out, this "battle" will not be able to fight, this pass will go wrong. I said to myself, if it kills me, get it out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 12,2020, Hu Junhua (left) was on the front line of the prevention and control inspection. Photograph: Shen Lin

At last, the solution came in time. Instead of giving the team time to mobilize, I told everyone to get to work, get to work, and then tell them: This is a serious state of war, we and the "enemy" is either dead or alive. This war with the virus, someone has to give, and if you're afraid, I won't go if you don't go, then all of us will end up dead.

In the first day or two of the inspection, there were a lot of vehicles at the crossing, and the longest stretch was one or two kilometers. I was under great pressure, not only to ensure strict inspection of each vehicle and each person, but also to constantly try to find ways to speed up the traffic speed, the mind and body can hardly stop for a moment.

Those days a few nights, the most difficult most tired time to get through. After that, it's all about persistence. The other people's police in the station, out of concern for epidemic prevention, are on duty for 14 days each, and are now in the third batch; while I and several other deputy station chiefs are not on duty, on duty every day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hu Junhua (right) and colleagues in the anti-epidemic work

Throughout the checkpoint, at the height of the outbreak, more than 900 people moved in, and I was responsible for everything. Carrying the double pressure of body and spirit, when I am really tired, I will find a place to sit and lean for a while. My heart beat a little early, this time of the chest sometimes dull pain, I am afraid of the problem, with the quick-effect heart pill, uncomfortable take a few tablets to ease.

The situation is constantly changing and the requirements for the work of the checkpoints are constantly changing. At first, it was necessary to solve the problem of waiting too long for traffic. Later, it was necessary to check the cars and persuade them to return. After the resumption of work, the number of logistics vehicles increased significantly.

Most of the time, I stayed up all night with my colleagues to figure out how to improve the solution. Honestly, with all the new ideas I keep coming up with, sometimes I feel like I'm running out of ideas. But I understand that this is a request for better prevention and control of the epidemic, so that more people are better protected.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hu jun-hua went to the vehicle control area through the underground passage. During the fight against the plague, he walked up and down this passage more than a dozen times a day.

In order to fight this battle well, we must do every little thing well. I had to protect our staff, and the hot ginger soup and heater had been arranged for them from the very beginning. The support force was constantly being replenished to the checkpoints, and I went over and over every detail of the job to everyone. At the beginning of the vehicle waiting for inspection time is longer, I saw some drivers really could not help but get off to the green belt to solve the "urgent" , immediately arranged to transfer to the temporary mobile toilet. A job like this, one day on the job, one day to consider and solve.

Before that, I had worked at this checkpoint for 15 years. Checkpoints at the site was originally and toll stations, beginning New Year's Day this year, cross-provincial toll stations canceled, my post from the previous checkpoint fixed point work, to be responsible for a certain section of the highway patrol inspection.

In my previous job, I was almost always at the checkpoint; after the change of work, though not really leaving, I was still very reluctant to leave. Over the years, I love the checkpoint as if it were my own child, guarding the pass as a career efforts, the checkpoint has become a branch of the flag. Unexpectedly, change less than a month, I came back in this form. Although the epidemic prevention work is not finished, but at least so far, I think, "southwest railway pass" reputation should be kept.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In 2019, Hu was stationed at a checkpoint. CCTV footage.

17 years ago, I fought an epidemic. I was in charge of logistics at the People's Liberation Army hospital 411, which also had an isolation ward for SARS. I had been behind the staff in quarantine gear, and I had been tired and struggling, but I had only one thing to do, and this new outbreak of pneumonia was a much bigger challenge. Seventeen years ago I was young and passionate, and now, 17 years later, I'm not young anymore, but I'm still in the mood.

I guess that's what the military did to me. As a young man, I served in the Marine Corps, where the requirements were as strict as those of the special forces. During the drill, I carried a gun and a backpack. I slept by my chair, ready to go to the front line and fight in the wind and waves. During the flood fighting, I fought against natural disasters. That's when I learned that service is a soldier's duty, no matter what the cost. Even though I've taken off my uniform, I still have that faith.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hu Junhua served in the Marine Corps. Hu Junhua contributed reporting

My family supported me in the fight against the plague. They understood that I was on a glorious mission, and they would remember that life was worth living. My son is now in the third day of junior high school. He is always clamoring to join the army in the future. My family used to live in Hongkou. I work here in Fengjing. It's 150 kilometers a day. To keep me from working too hard, my wife quit her job a few years ago and asked me to move to Songjiang District.

February 20th is my 50th birthday. One day I was at my checkpoint when my wife called me up and said she had ordered a song for me on the radio to wish me a happy birthday. When I heard it, I was familiar with Aaron Kwok's endless love for you when I was young. I'm surprised and touched. Thank you.

Photo courtesy of the Songjiang District Branch of the Shanghai Public Security Bureau.
